    },
    {
      "type": "reading",
      "title": "Reading Text: The Legend of the Leprechaun",
      "introduction": "We will read a short text about a famous Irish legend, the Leprechaun. Pay attention to the details of the story and the vocabulary used.",
      "paragraphs": [
        "Leprechauns are small, mischievous creatures from Irish folklore. They are said to be shoemakers who guard pots of gold at the end of rainbows.  These elusive beings are rarely seen, adding to the mystery surrounding them.",
        "According to legend, if you catch a leprechaun, he will be forced to reveal the location of his hidden treasure. However, it's said that leprechauns are incredibly tricky and will often lead you on a wild goose chase, making it nearly impossible to find the gold.",
        "The legend of the leprechaun reflects a deeper cultural belief in hidden fortunes and the importance of luck. It also highlights the dangers of greed and the potential for deception.  The story continues to capture imaginations worldwide."
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "vocabulary",
      "title": "Key Vocabulary",
      "words": [
        {
          "term": "mischievous",
          "partOfSpeech": "adjective",
          "definition": "Naughty; playfully causing trouble.",
          "example": "The mischievous children played pranks on their neighbors."
        },
        {
          "term": "elusive",
          "partOfSpeech": "adjective",
          "definition": "Difficult to find, catch, or achieve.",
          "example": "The elusive thief managed to escape the police."
        },
        {
          "term": "legend",
          "partOfSpeech": "noun",
          "definition": "A traditional story sometimes popularly regarded as historical but unauthenticated.",
          "example": "The legend of King Arthur is well-known."
        },
        {
          "term": "folklore",
          "partOfSpeech": "noun",
          "definition": "The traditional beliefs, customs, and stories of a community, passed through generations by word of mouth.",
          "example": "Irish folklore is rich with tales of fairies and mythical creatures."
        },
        {
          "term": "deception",
          "partOfSpeech": "noun",
          "definition": "The action of deceiving someone.",
          "example": "He was found guilty of deception and fraud."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "comprehension",
      "title": "Comprehension Questions",
      "questions": [
        {
          "question": "What is a leprechaun, according to the text?",
